<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Broker support lifts BT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON.
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BT consolidated its position as the UK's biggest company, measured by market
capitalisation, following a strong buy recommendation from Robert Fleming
Securities. BT fully-paid shares settled 6 1/2 firmer at 383p and the
partly-paid 5 1/2 up at 264 1/2 p. Combined turnover in the two classes of
stock was 19.6m shares.
Mr Laurence Heyworth, telecoms analyst at the stockbroker, set a short term
target price of 420p for the fully-paid shares, telling clients that BT's
first-quarter figures expected on July 25 should please the market. Fleming
expects profits of around Pounds 750m, with inland call volume growth
estimated at 6 to 7 per cent, against 2 per cent last year. 'A little good
news could provide a powerful stimulus to the shares,' said Mr Heyworth.
The analyst added that BT had become very attractive. 'In addition to the
yield and price/earnings ratio, BT's firm value per line (ie market
capitalisation plus debt divided by the number of fixed lines) is now only
Dollars 1,430, the lowest of the quoted European telecom companies,' he
said.
</TEXT>
