<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets: F&amp;C targets emerging markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign &amp; Colonial believes the time is right to be moving back into the
emerging markets, including some - like Hong Kong, Malaysia and Thailand -
which have been hardest hit in the recent downturn. Mr Arnab Banerji, F &amp;
C's chief investment officer, told an investment gathering last night that
over the last 20 years there were four occasions when emerging markets fell
by the magnitude seen in recent months. During the early 1980s the markets
were stagnant for two years, but this coincided with the global recession
and the Latin American debt crisis. On other occasions, the downturn lasted
for no more than eight months. Each downturn had followed a rise in US
interest rates, along the lines of that seen in late February. All were
terminated by a recovery, driven by strong OECD growth. With the US economy
strong, the UK recovering, Germany recording expansion and Japan at or near
the bottom of its business cycle, Mr Banerji sees the right conditions to
start buying again.
