London Page 38
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT943-15748</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EGGDZAGNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Survey of Italy (9): Catalyst for change - Privatisation and
the new government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In less than two years, privatisation, once anathema to Italian governments,
has suddenly become a benchmark for judging Rome's commitment to modernising
the Italian economy.
The three-year programme launched by the Amato government in July 1992
seemed to move slowly or not at all at the start. But when Efim, the now
defunct state holding company, completed the sale of its glass-making
subsidiary SIV to the UK's Pilkington last June, it signalled an
acceleration of the process.
Since then, there have been at least seven substantial sales, raising more
than L13,000bn, not to mention a number of smaller flotations and private
sales, for example by Eni, the state energy and chemicals group. Earlier
this week, the Treasury was completing the largest privatisation yet - the
sale of 51 per cent of Ina, the insurance company. In theory, the market
will soon have to digest the even larger privatisations of Stet, the
telecommunications holding company, Enel, the electricity generator, and all
or part of Eni.
Everybody seems to agree that the process of Italian privatisation is now
unstoppable. One of the first things Mr Silvio Berlusconi's new
administration did in May, when confirmed in office, was to press ahead with
the flotation timetable of Ina, as a signal of its willingness to carry out
the programme outlined by Mr Giuliano Amato and pursued by his successor, Mr
Carlo Azeglio Ciampi.
Mr Giancarlo Pagliarini, the new budget minister, said last month that the
government's privatisation ambitions would extend to the contracting out of
services. 'For this government, privatisation doesn't only mean selling
state enterprises,' he told foreign journalists in Milan. 'The sales are
only a small part of the privatisation programme.'
Most of the reasons why the state sell-off is important to the Berlusconi
administration are fairly orthodox.
The proceeds of the sell-offs are channelled into reducing public
indebtedness, helping to prevent a spiralling increase in the deficit and
interest payments which could undermine all Mr Berlusconi's economic
promises. Privatisation also helps public finances because it puts an end to
most state subsidies. That, in turn, helps convince foreign governments and
pan-European authorities that Italy is not going to slide back into its old
trade-distorting habits.
For example, in the case of Ilva, the loss-making state steel producer, the
fact that the Ciampi government's plans involved a commitment to the
division and sale of its main operations helped to persuade the European
Commission to approve a final package of subsidies for the company.
The final motive for continuing with privatisation is to encourage the Milan
stock market. Apart from the interim Amato and Ciampi administrations, the
Berlusconi government is the first in Italian postwar history that actively
wants to stimulate the private sector through the stock market.
Privatisation is one of the catalysts which the stock exchange and the
government hope will encourage wider share ownership and the flotation of
more private companies.
As Mr Pietro Armani, a former deputy chairman of Iri, the main state holding
company, said at a recent conference on privatisation: 'It is no longer
possible today to think of a return to a mixed economy with direct state
control of enterprises . . . That's not only because of the strictures of
the EU, but also because the state can perfectly well control the economy
indirectly, through 'golden shares'.'
However, in practice, some of the government's ambitions have been thwarted
by circumstances. It is proving difficult to sell certain parts of the state
sector - notably the flat steel division of Ilva, and the GS/Autogrill
supermarket and catering companies. In addition, the previous
administration's privatisation of two banks, Credito Italiano and Banca
Commerciale Italiana, has sparked controversy about the control of such
companies, casting a long shadow over future plans.
Mr Romano Prodi, then chairman of Iri, has led protests that powerful
corporate and financial allies - backed by Mediobanca, the Milan merchant
bank - gained control over the boards of the two banks after privatisation,
by pooling their shares to nominate directors. According to Mr Prodi and his
supporters, this circumvented rules limiting individual shareholders to a 3
per cent stake in the company, and thus thwarted Iri's attempts to encourage
wider share ownership.
Neutral observers have pointed out that until Italy develops a pension fund
and unit trust industry along Anglo-Saxon lines it will be difficult to
guarantee small shareholders a voice in privatised boardrooms. In addition,
Mr Prodi's opponents - such as Mr Paolo Savona, former industry minister -
say the establishment of a nocciolo duro or hard core of shareholders helps
privatised companies.
But the new government has still felt moved to dispel the small
shareholders' fears. In the case of Ina, a 5 per cent limit has been imposed
on shareholdings, but the stakes of allies - for example, investors who are
members of the shareholder syndicate of third companies - will be counted as
belonging to a single investor. At the same time, a certain number of seats
on the board will be reserved for small shareholders' nominees. Although it
remains to be seen how these rules will work in practice, the government has
indicated that they will apply to the much more sensitive sell-offs of Enel
and Stet.
These sales, and that of Eni, will be the real test for the new government's
professed enthusiasm for privatisation, partly because they are larger than
anything which has gone before. The Stet offer could set Mediobanca directly
against supporters of wider share ownership, because the merchant bank wants
to form a shareholder syndicate with Pirelli, the tyres and cables group, to
take control of the telecoms company. Critics say links between Pirelli and
one of its principal potential customers would hold back the development of
Stet.
There is also a running debate about how and when to privatise Enel and the
oil and gas interests of Eni. In theory, Stet should be sold before the end
of this year, and Enel shortly afterwards. But Eni is pushing hard for the
government to consider selling its Agip and Snam oil and gas subsidiaries
before Enel comes to the market. 'We've done everything to prepare for the
government to take a final decision,' says Mr Franco Bernabe, Eni's chief
executive.
Critics of the government say it was not too difficult to take a quick
decision about the sale of Ina, because it was uncontroversial and the
ground had been well-prepared by treasury officials. It may prove more
difficult to realise the high-sounding promises of Mr Berlusconi and his
ministers to implement quickly the rest of the privatisation programme.
