<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Oceans set to yield up their
treasures - Canute James reports on the agreement of an international code
of conduct for seabed mining after 11 years of negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After 11 years of tortuous and often contentious negotiations, agreement has
been reached on a code of conduct for mining the international seabed.
The agreement, which hinged on convincing industrialised countries that
commercial principles would be observed, is to be be adopted by the United
Nations general assembly this month. It will allow the establishment of the
International Seabed Authority, a new UN agency, which will administer the
Law of the Sea Convention, and will create the Enterprise, the authority's
commercial arm, which will oversee exploration and mining through joint
ventures among private companies and states.
The agreement will also create a tribunal that will adjudicate disputes over
seabed mining among states and companies.
The authority and the Enterprise will be located in Jamaica, while the
tribunal will be in Hamburg, Germany.
At the centre of the debates in the UN Law of the Sea Conference, which
sought general acceptance of the convention are the trillions of dollars
worth of polymetallic nodules that are lying on the international seabed,
outside the 200-mile economic zone of any country. The nodules contain
copper, nickel, manganese and cobalt, and varying quantities of other
minerals.
'The intention was to find an orderly method of dealing with minerals
located on the international seabed,' says Mr Kenneth Rattray, rapporteur
general of the Law of the Sea Conference.
'Since these minerals are outside the economic zones of states, it was
important to have an acceptance by all countries that the minerals did not
belong to any one state or private company, but were the common heritage of
all mankind.
'This is an attempt to avert anarchy in mining the international seabed and
to permit orderly exploration and exploitation within a regulatory
framework.'
While developing countries have always been in favour of a convention to
regulate the mining of the international seabed, the discussions were
protracted because of reservations that industrialised states had about the
commercial feasibility of the proposals, and about the sharing of costs and
benefits. In its original form the Law of the Sea Convention was not clear
on the role private business would play in seabed mining, and on how the
technology would be obtained.
Fundamental changes in the world economy, the move by governments away from
central planning to market-based economies and the growing role for private
business, all precluded the creation of an economic agency in which only
governments would be involved.
Under the draft of the convention, the Enterprise was to have been funded by
the member states based on subscriptions and loans, with the first mining
venture estimated to cost about USDollars 1bn. 'Philosophical and economic
arguments indicated that this was not the most desired method, so it was
agreed that the first operation of the enterprise will be done as a joint
venture with the partners providing the investment, on the now accepted
basis that the international seabed is the common heritage of mankind,'
explains Mr Rattray.
'The enterprise is the only way for poorer countries to participate. Some
developed states wanted the Enterprise to be abolished, but it was agreed
that after its first venture the Enterprise will begin operating on a purely
commercial basis.'
There were also concerns among the industrialised states about the transfer
of technology. Since private business, and not governments, own the
technology, members of the UN were unable to get access to it. In the
accord, it has been accepted that if the technology is not available on the
market at commercially fair terms, governments would co-operate with the
International Seabed Authority to make it available. 'This is intended to
give the Enterprise a jump start,' says Mr Rattray.
One of the more fundamental concerns about seabed mining, and in which both
developed and developing countries had common concerns, was the effect the
extraction of the polymetalic nodules and production of the minerals would
have on land-based producers.
While most states eschewed production ceilings, saying this method was an
echo of central planning, land-based producers argued that there could be
unfair economic practices in seabed mining, which could lead to a flooding
of markets and depressed prices. There will be no production limits, but the
principles of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade on unfair
competition have been adopted in the Law of the Sea Convention.
Production plans will include an estimate of the maximum quantity of
minerals to be produced each year and there will be a compensation fund for
land-based producers who are adversely affected by seabed mining.
'The original expectation when the conference began 11 years ago was that
seabed mining would have started by 1998,' says Mr Rattray. 'This was not
achieved because of real and philosophical changes in the world economy.
With this agreement, commercial production from the seabed is now expected
to begin in another 10 years.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
