<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / International Bonds: Borrowers take advantage of re-awakened
eurolira sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After a lull due to the volatility of the Italian government bond market,
three borrowers took advantage of renewed interest in the eurolira market
and attractive swap opportunities to launch L700bn-worth of issues
yesterday.
Dealers said swap opportunities had been available for a week or more, as
the gap between the secondary eurolira bond market and the lira swaps market
widened, allowing deals to be priced with double-digit coupons.
The growing yield differential between German and Italian bonds and the
perceived weakness of the lira then started to attract retail investors and
portfolio managers back to the eurolira market, in spite of continuing
nervousness about the Italian government bond market.
Austria's Osterreichische Kontrollbank launched the first of the three
five-year issues, a L200bn offering of 10 per cent bonds arranged by Swiss
Bank Corporation, followed by a L200bn deal with a 10 1/4 per cent coupon
for Deutsche Bank.
The third deal off the blocks was a L300bn offering for Commerzbank,
arranged by IMI Bank.
The issue made up for its late arrival and slightly lower rating (the other
two are both rated triple-A) with a 10 1/2 per cent coupon.
In spite of concern that the heavy flow of paper would quickly exhaust
interest, dealers reported demand from Germany, Switzerland and the Benelux
region. The concentration on the five-year area, where the best swap rates
were available, suited retail investors.
Two large yen offerings for the Province of British Colombia, which launched
three small deals in the sector on Tuesday, and the Kingdom of Sweden were
driven by strong demand for yen assets from Japanese investors. Japanese
institutions had been selling US bonds due to currency concerns and were
cash-rich, dealers said.
The 4 per cent coupon on British Colombia's five-year issue via Daiwa and
the 3.10 per cent coupon on Sweden's short-dated deal arranged by IBJ proved
attractive, according to traders, as Japanese investors such as insurance
companies are interested in coupon rather than yield spread levels.
In the D-Mark sector, the triple-A rated City of Paris launched its first
foreign currency bond offering, a DM130m five-year deal arranged by Banque
Paribas. Decentralisation has allowed French municipalities greater freedom
to diversify their funding, which traditionally has mainly come from the
French agency, Credit Local de France.
The deal was targeted at retail investors in Germany, Switzerland and the
Benelux region.
In the dollar market, Essar Gujarat, the Indian steel company, launched the
first floating-rate note by a private-sector Indian company. The deal was
broadly placed with institutions according to lead manager Chase Investment
Bank.
</TEXT>
