<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / UK Company News: BDA chairman faces threat of removal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two non-executive directors of BDA Holdings are requisitioning an
extraordinary general meeting to oust Mr Brian Duker as chairman and chief
executive of the property investment and development group.
Mr Richard Wollenberg, BDA's non-executive deputy chairman and Mr Nigel
Jamieson together hold about 3.1 per cent of the company, while Mr
Wollenberg is also a director of Village Residential, which has a 13 per
cent stake.
Mr Wollenberg said BDA needed to expand its interests and he had 'lost
confidence in Mr Duker's ability to take the company forward'. He claimed
support from shareholders, including several large institutions, speaking
for 51.33 per cent of the votes.
Mr Duker, who controls about 24 per cent of BDA, said he had 'brought the
company back from the brink of disaster over the last few years'. He said he
would be writing to shareholders in due course.
In April, BDA reported a turnround from Pounds 1.16m losses to pre-tax
profits of Pounds 152,000 in the year to end January 1994, after a release
of property provisions of Pounds 100,000, compared with a Pounds 1.2m charge
before.
