<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / G7 attacked for failing to cope with global monetary reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Reform of the global monetary system is urgently needed to reduce exchange
rate volatility, an independent group of experts headed by Mr Paul Volcker,
the former chairman of the US Federal Reserve, said yesterday.
The group criticised the consultative process of the Group of Seven leading
industrial countries for failing to cope with the task and suggested that it
should be done instead by the International Monetary Fund with redefined
responsibilities.
The recommendations came in a report released yesterday by the Bretton Woods
Commission, which includes former senior ministers, central bankers and
private sector representatives. It urges sweeping reforms of the IMF and the
World Bank to reflect big changes in the financial environment.
The group said a long-term goal should be to establish 'a flexible system of
exchange rate bands' - or currency target zones - between the dollar, yen
and D-Mark.
However, a more stable exchange rate system would be feasible only if the
leading industrial countries reduced macroeconomic imbalances and achieved
greater economic convergence - for example, on inflation rates.
The experts said the costs of exchange rate misalignment and volatility were
high and had contributed to a halving of the long-term growth rate of
industrial countries to about 2.5 per cent a year from 5 per cent before the
collapse of the Bretton Woods exchange rate system in the early 1970s.
The alternative to reform was 'to continue the present non-system of loose
ad hoc co-operation, dominated by the G7 process'. That was unlikely to lead
to 'economic policies that are sound internationally as well as
domestically'.
While the impetus for reform had to come from the leading industrial
countries, the G7 process was not the best means to support the sustained
reform effort required. 'The G7 process is not an institution, a continuing
body, or an executive entity.' Its representation was narrow and it did not
even have a secretariat.
The experts said the task of devising and implementing a reform of the
global financial system should be entrusted to the IMF, which had 'much of
the necessary expertise'.
They said the IMF should concentrate on its global monetary responsibilities
and stop acting as a development agency - a role in which the World Bank had
a greater comparative advantage.
IMF and World Bank must adapt, Page 5
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
