<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Water bills may rise to meet extra Pounds 520m in clean-up
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British householders could face even higher water bills next year as a way
of meeting additional environmental obligations handed to the water
companies yesterday by Mr John Gummer, environment secretary.
The government added another Pounds 522m to the bill water companies must
pay for treating sewage and cleaning up rivers over the next five years. Mr
Gummer told the industry regulator, Mr Ian Byatt, to take the additional
funding into account when fixing price limits for domestic bills.
The new money is equal to about Pounds 6 a year for each of Britain's 18m
households, but bills will rise more in some areas than in others.
Price formulas for Britain's 31 water companies are due to be announced on
July 28. They will already take into account a Pounds 14bn-Pounds 15bn
clean-up of waste water planned by the industry by 2000.
Mr Gummer's decision to add another Pounds 500m in environmental spending to
companies' obligations will inevitably lead to the charge that householders
will end up footing the bill. Water companies have increased their charges
to households by 67 per cent since privatisation in 1989.
'Consumers have been asked to pay a very large part of the burden of
investment and general upkeep of the system since privatisation,' said an
official at the National Consumers' Council. 'But there is no reason why the
cost of this environmental spending should be passed on.'
The consumers' council says the burden placed on householders is 'unfair'.
Companies should turn to other sources of finance such as the equity market
for investment capital. The council is to publish a report on water price
increases on Monday.
Companies hit hardest by the additional environmental spending will be North
West Water, which will be required to pay Pounds 130m for cleaning up the
Mersey basin, and Severn Trent Water, which will face an increase of Pounds
194m. The funds will be used to clean up sewage that is discharged into
rivers in particularly sensitive areas.
Mr Andrew Wheeler, a broker at NatWest Securities in London, said that the
additional spending would not make much difference to overall bills: 'When
you're looking at investment of Pounds 15bn, an extra Pounds 500m doesn't
seem that much,' he said.
</TEXT>
