FT  07 JUL 94 / Heritage secretary receives praise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary, yesterday received a wide measure of
praise for the long-awaited white paper as well a few jeers from unrepentant
privatisers who greeted the announcement with cries of 'shame', 'rubbish'
and 'cop-out'.
Mr Tim Renton, a former broadcasting minister, congratulated Mr Brooke for
resisting the temptation to go for too much change.
At a time when there was a vast increase in the number of television and
radio channels in the UK people 'actually welcome the BBC as a sort of
friendly 'rock of ages',' he said.
Mr David Mellor, former heritage secretary, emphasised that the present
outcome had been possible only because of radical changes introduced at the
corporation.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, shadow heritage secretary, welcomed the government's
endorsement of the licence fee but said she was concerned because there was
no commitment to index it to retail prices.
Mr Robert Maclennan, for the Liberal Democrats, welcomed the renewal of the
royal charter and licence fee but called for an independent regulator for
all television.
Mr Gerald Kaufman, chairman of the Commons heritage committee, said the BBC
should consider creating links with telecommunications organisations.
He told Mr Brooke: 'What the BBC has to do is either dwindle into a
low-audience public service broadcast service or become what you have
rightly said it should become, an international multimedia enterprise.'
