<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Britvic censured over TV advert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission, the commercial television watchdog,
yesterday strongly criticised a publicity stunt by Britvic Soft Drinks which
was judged to 'abuse the authority of the television medium and trespass on
public confidence'.
The television advertisement in May, for a drink called Still Tango,
featured Tango's marketing director in a spoof warning to the public that
the product was unauthorised. Viewers were urged to ring a freephone number
to report stockists.
When viewers called - and the company says 30,000 people responded on the
first night - they were told that they had been tricked and were offered a
voucher for the drink.
Coincidentally, Britvic had to recall all bottles of the new drink a week
later because of 'a small number of cases of fermentation' which were said
not to pose a health hazard but had caused distorted packaging and a musty
smell. To get the recall taken seriously, the company was forced in press
advertisements to distance itself from the spoof TV warnings.
The ITC said that 63 viewers had complained that 'it was not appropriate to
use television advertising to play practical jokes on viewers'. Some also
said 'they had been alarmed because they thought that a health hazard was
being implied'.
The ITC, which ruled that such advertisements should not be shown in future,
concluded: 'If this was not quite setting off the fire alarm for a laugh it
was certainly ringing door bells and running away.'
Britvic said yesterday that the company was sorry if it had caused offence.
'The target market is young adults who are very much 'advertising aware' and
enjoy our tongue-in-cheek approach,' it added.
Separately, the ITC yesterday published its 1993 annual report which covers
the first year of operation of the 16 new Channel 3 licensees.
</TEXT>
