<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Regulator calls for rules on short selling of shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New rules are needed to govern short selling of a company's shares just
before a secondary offering of those shares hits the market, London's chief
regulator said yesterday.
Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, was
outlining the preliminary conclusions from a review of wider market issues
which the regulatory body launched in February.
Short selling is the practice of selling shares one does not already own in
the hope of buying them more cheaply by the time it is necessary to deliver
them to the buyer. A secondary offering of the same company's shares could,
in theory, allow an investor the opportunity to buy those shares more
cheaply than he or she had sold them and use the cheaper shares to cover a
short position.
Mr Large ruled out significant changes to rules which allow those who commit
their own capital to provide liquidity for share dealing to hide some of
their deals from competitors for a period.
Speaking at a Financial Times conference on international equity markets, he
said: 'Few, I think, question the need for requiring less than full
transparency where people oblige themselves to put up their capital to
deliver liquidity.'
But he suggested that in some instances rules allowed dealing to be opaque
for much longer than was necessary.
Mr Large said SIB had received considerable comment from market participants
on the issue of short selling. 'From a regulatory viewpoint, the priority
seems to me to be the search for better procedures to cover short selling
during secondary offering periods,' he said.
He noted that the London Stock Exchange had been examining the issue and
said that solutions were 'a matter of urgency'.
The question of short selling and outright selling before a secondary
offering came to a head last summer before the government's sale of its
final stake in British Telecommunications. SG Warburg, the merchant bank
advising the government, asked the Stock Exchange to adopt rules for trading
in BT shares designed to make short sales or outright sales difficult.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
