<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / BBC role and funding reinforced by review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC yesterday emerged virtually unscathed from three years of intense
government scrutiny. Its structure and its financing by universal licence
fee were left intact and its public-service purpose underpinned.
The white paper that will form the heart of a new royal charter to run for
10 years from the beginning of 1997 is entitled The Future of the BBC -
Serving the Nation, Competing Worldwide.
The title sets out explicitly a dual future for the BBC. It is the role the
corporation was asking to be allowed to play - as the UK's main
public-service broadcaster developing commercial services in the UK and
overseas.
Although the government believes that the corporation's primary role should
remain as a public-service broadcaster to the UK, it equally clearly hopes
it will be able 'to evolve into an international multimedia enterprise'.
The BBC will retain all its radio and television services although the
government wants to see clear objectives set for what those services should
be. The corporation can then be assessed on how successfully the objectives
have been met.
The white paper says: 'The government agrees that the BBC should continue to
broadcast a wide range of television and radio programmes which will appeal
to all tastes and interests and to people of different ages and backgrounds
and living in all parts of the country.'
While programmes aimed at minorities were an important part of the BBC's
role, the public wanted it to continue producing popular programmes capable
of attracting audiences of 10m to 20m and a wide range of radio programmes
including popular music.
The government would like to see more programmes featuring science and
engineering, more programmes reflecting life in the regions of the UK and
greater sensitivity in terms of what audiences find acceptable in matters of
taste and decency.
Until the end of next year - when the current charter runs out - the BBC
will be funded by a licence fee linked to the retail prices index. The
licence fee will continue at least until the year 2001, when it will be
reviewed in the light of changing technology and other developments. To set
the licence fee from 1997 to 2001 the government will consider a link with
the retail prices index.
The government even suggested yesterday that the licence fee could rise in
real terms if the BBC could demonstrate that costs over which it had little
control - such as sports rights and talent - were rising particularly
rapidly.
The main barb for the BBC in the white paper was over its transmitters. The
government is clearly linking the BBC's hopes of entering the world of
digital television - which could greatly increase the number of television
channels using terrestrial transmitters - with introducing an element of
private finance.
The white paper says: 'The government is exploring with the BBC options for
the future of its transmission services, taking account of the development
of its plans for digital broadcasting.' A study is due to be completed this
year and privatisation of the whole or part of the BBC transmitter services
will be options.
The most remarkable part of the white paper is the high degree of
encouragement the government is giving to the BBC to develop commercial
television and radio services around the world, using its expertise in World
Service Radio and the developing Worldwide Television services.
As long as there is no cross-subsidy from the licence fee or the grant that
funds the World Service, and as long as there is transparent accounting and
fair pricing, the BBC has been liberated to compete in broadcasting markets
around the world and in the UK.
The new commercial activities should, however, be underpinned by the BBC's
longer-term objectives and its values as a public-service broadcaster. To
help the process the government plans to repeal legislation preventing the
Independent Television Commission and the Radio Authority from 'licensing
commercial services which are owned or partly owned by the BBC'.
Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary, said the measure was an
enabling one and declined to say whether the BBC would be able to be
involved in applying for commercial broadcasting licences in the UK. At the
very least the policy should mean that the BBC will be able to aim satellite
services at the UK as well as the international market.
Because the next 10 years will almost certainly see a period of significant
change in demand for media services, the government wants the BBC to keep
its options open for further development by building up its commercial
activities and expertise, and widening its sources of income.
The white paper says: 'It can do this by increasing its international
activities, maintaining its capacity for programme-making and contributing
to improving the UK's competitiveness in the audio-visual sector in the
years ahead.'
The white paper also wants a clearer separation of the role of the BBC
governors and management. 'The governor's role is to look after the public's
interest in the BBC not to manage it,' it says.
The government said yesterday that it planned to merge the Broadcasting
Complaints Commission and the Broadcasting Standards Council, but rejected
calls for one authority for all British broadcasting.
With the exception of the section on transmitters and some complaints about
the BBC's lack of responsiveness to its audience, the degree of consensus is
so great that the BBC could almost have written the document itself.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
How to serve the nation and compete worldwide
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 - BBC should split public service and commercial activities and evolve
into a multimedia enterprise, using opportunites created by new
technologies.
 - Programmes sales should be expanded, and international services
developed in co-operation with private sector
 - Public services should remain distinct, financed by the licence fee
 - Clear objectives for each service should be published and audience
consulted on changes
 - Broadcasting Complaints Commission and Broadcasting Standards
Council should merge
 - Privatisation to be considered among options for injecting private
finance into transmission services
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
