<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Authority to oppose BAe airport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace's con-troversial attempt to develop its Filton airfield
near Bristol as a commercial airport is to be opposed by the local planning
authority, Roland Adburgham writes.
A public inquiry into the scheme is to be held after BAe appealed to the
environment secretary. This followed the delay by Northavon district council
in deciding on the application, which was submitted last September.
Northavon council yesterday unanimously decided that, had it still been in a
position to decide on the application, it would have refused it because of
the airport's adverse environmental impact, especially on noise levels. The
council's officers had recommended refusal.
BAe wants to have scheduled services to make more use of its Filton runway.
It believes this would help to safeguard the future of its adjacent plant,
where 5,000 people are employed. Although the plans are supported by many in
the region's business community there is vociferous opposition from local
residents.
</TEXT>
