<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Output up 1.3% in quarter: Pharmaceuticals and furniture
rise while footwear declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Production of cars, pharmaceuticals, plastic packaging and furniture rose in
May, while footwear and ship-building dipped slightly, official figures
showed yesterday.
Overall, industrial output showed a healthy 1.3 per cent growth in the three
months to May compared with the three months to February, and a 4.6 per cent
growth over the same period a year ago, the Central Statistical Office said.
On a monthly basis output rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.3 per cent between
April and May.
This growth rate was slower than in April, when output unexpectedly surged
1.6 per cent on the month.
The figure was in line with City expectations, however, and analysts
yesterday welcomed it as evidence of a healthily steady industrial recovery.
They pointed out that, if April's surge had been repeated in May, this might
have prompted fears that the industrial recovery was overheating and
fuelling inflationary pressures.
Within the quarterly figures, manufacturing rose 1.2 per cent in the three
months to May compared with the previous three months.
Meanwhile oil and gas continued to boost the production figures, as a
collection of new North Sea fields came on stream in recent months. Although
oil and gas production dipped slightly in May because of an accident on the
Piper Alpha field it is now running 39.6 per cent higher than in the same
period a year ago.
Across other sectors the manufacturing rise was fairly broadly based,
suggesting that the recovery is feeding through to all stages in the
industrial supply chain.
The output of the investment goods industry rose 1.5 per cent in the three
months to May, compared with the previous three months, while consumer goods
output rose 1 per cent. Intermediate goods industries, which supply
manufacturers with their energy, components and raw materials, rose 1.4 per
cent in the same period.
Pharmaceuticals performed particularly well, rising 3 per cent, quarter on
quarter. The plastics packaging business - often a key to signs of recovery
in other manufacturing areas - rose 4 per cent in the same period.
Furniture and car production also showed healthy rises, while electrical and
optical equipment manufacturers were the best performing engineering sector,
rising 3.3 per cent in the three months to May compared with the previous
quarter.
The CSO said this growth had been boosted by particularly strong output in
the computer, telephone and electrical goods industry.
Footwear production, however, fell 5 per cent in the quarter. The
shipbuilding and aerospace industries continued to report a slowdown, with
the output of both categories running 10 per cent lower than in the previous
year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
