<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Railtrack to clarify pay package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack is to clarify and may revise its productivity pay package for
signalling staff, the company said yesterday as it claimed that nearly 20
per cent of Britain's 10,000-mile rail network was open on the fourth
one-day signallers' strike.
It said the move was in response to suggestions from staff who have
responded to the company's 'hearts and minds' campaign launched last
weekend.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT transport union's general secretary, said the
support for the strike yesterday indicated that the men had 'given
Railtrack's latest offer the thumbs-down'.
Support for yesterday's strike - the fourth on consecutive Wednesdays -
appeared to be solid.
Further one-day strikes are scheduled for the next two Wednesdays, with the
threat of two-day a week strikes after July 24.
The company seems to believe that it can go over the heads of the RMT and
convince staff that the tentative offer on the bargaining table can meet
their grievances.
A Railtrack official said: 'If we cannot negotiate with their union, at
least we can negotiate direct with the signalling staff.'
The company is keen, in particular, to reassure signalling staff who face
cuts in pre-tax pay as a result of efficiency savings that they will receive
substantial compensation payments.
In response to public pressure from MPs on the cross-party Commons
employment committee, Railtrack's chairman Mr Robert Horton met Mr Knapp
yesterday.
In a joint statement after their two-hour meeting in London the two men said
they had 'exchanged views and agreed to reflect on what was said'.
British Rail yesterday ran a more comprehensive service than on any of the
previous strike days, with between 1,700 and 1,750 trains in operation.
Private companies ran significant freight services for the first time with
trains moving aggregates between the Mendips and London.
Passenger services operated for the first time from London Victoria and
Waterloo stations.
Traffic into London and other large cities was light, as motorists staggered
journeys to avoid congestion.
West Midlands Passenger Transport Authority is likely to withhold Pounds 2m
from Regional Railways Central - 40 per cent of the subsidy to the train
operating company for running services during the quarter to June.
Centro, the authority's operating arm, said that since the break-up of the
industry on April 1 'only 60.5 per cent of Centro subsidised services on
seven local lines ran to within three minutes of timetable'.
</TEXT>
