<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Bar says QC rank should be retained
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bar has come down in favour of retaining the present system for
appointing Queen's Counsel in spite of criticism from barristers that the
system is secretive and open to abuse.
A working party chaired by Mr Michael Kalisher QC says in a report published
today that the present system of appointment by the Queen on the advice of
the Lord Chancellor is preferable to alternatives such as appointment by an
independent commission, or by the Bar itself.
The Bar favours retaining the rank of QC because it helps the public and
solicitors identify barristers of a recognised high standard. But it
recognises that changes would have to be made to the present system to meet
the concerns of many barristers.
The report recommends publication of formal criteria for getting silk,
including outstanding ability as an advocate, experience and knowledge of
the law, professional integrity and an extensive practice.
The report says appointments should be solely on merit, with no positive
discrimination in favour of women or ethnic minorities. The number of
appointments should remain low to underline the importance of the rank but
numbers should not be artificially restricted.
Applications have risen from 204 in 1985, when 34 were appointed, to 539 in
1994, when 77 were appointed. The barristers say the high number of
applicants threatens the efficacy of the system as the judges and senior
barristers who are consulted on appointments cannot give every application
the consideration it requires.
A limit on the number of applications should be considered and barristers
should be discouraged from applying prematurely.
The report says there is no justification for any part of the process to
remain secret. Guidance notes should set out precisely how the system works
and identify all those consulted. Applicants should be told in general terms
what has been said about them and what impact this has had.
Unsuccessful applicants should be told broadly why they have failed and that
they are entitled to seek an interview at the Lord Chancellor's Department
to be told in more detail why they have been unsuccessful.
</TEXT>
