<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Power companies accused over databases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some electricity distribution companies are breaking the law by using
customer databases to promote services other than electricity, the Data
Protection Registrar said yesterday in a statement which has implications
for all privatised utilities.
Mr Eric Howe, the registrar, also raised the prospect of conflict between
the data protection office and the financial services industry over the
confidentiality of personal financial information. He said in his annual
report that he believed a number of current and planned uses of customer
data information by regional electricity companies in England and Wales were
in contravention of data protection law.
He said that under the Electricity and Data Protection Acts it was illegal
for companies either to use their customer mailings as 'host' for
non-electricity promotions or to pass names and addresses to commercial
third parties. 'There may be implications for the activities or proposed
activities of other utilities,' he said.
Mr Howe intends to write to the electricity companies and to consult the
utility regulators on the issue.
But he 'anticipated' that his successor as registrar, who takes office in
September, would issue formal guidance in the next year.
But the registrar's office left the legal position ambivalent by adding that
it might be possible for the electricity companies to use personal data in
some cases provided they offered customers a chance to opt out. At present
few utilities use their databases for more than customer-client
administration, but many are believed to be considering doing so as a means
of generating new earnings.
Eastern Electricity said Mr Howe's statement 'added to existing legal
ambiguity' over the use of customer data and that it would approach the
Department of Trade and Industry for clarifi-cation.
Mr Howe said legal action between the financial services industry and the
data protection office could take place in months following a paper
circulated by the registrar earlier this year over the disclosure of
information about customers.
The paper said that disclosure of personal financial information could only
follow specific consent from the individuals concerned, and that such
consent might in any case be insufficient under a European Union directive
set to be enshrined in UK law.
The paper has met a hostile reaction from the financial services industry,
including one claim that it amounted to a 'fraudsters' charter'.
Mr Howe said a response from the government appeared to support his legal
view.
Mr Howe said he was 'not unsympathetic' to arguments that defaulters on
loans should lose some rights to confidentiality.
He remained convinced, however, that 'those who do service debts properly
should have control over whether their financial affairs should be revealed
to others'.
Mr Howe also raised concerns about the introduction of national
identification through policies such as driving licences with photos, social
security 'swipe' cards and the use of national insurance and national health
service numbers for new purposes.
He said: 'The issue is too fundamental for the UK to allow itself simply to
slip into having a de facto national identification system without the
necessary safeguards and restrictions.'
</TEXT>
