<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Political Notebook: Time to make common cause on pay and
jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Let us get one or two things clear. The debate about the relationship
between jobs, pay and benefits will not go away. Politicians cannot ignore
the structural shifts in the economy which are driving down the wages and
the employment opportunities of the unskilled. But sound-bite politics and
complex economics make uneasy bedfellows.
The debate will become a serious one only when politicians recognise that
neither the market nor government alone offers simple solutions, and when
they address the electorate in terms which illuminate rather than obscure
the arguments.
Take the fashionable phrase of the moment. When Labour leadership contender
Mr Tony Blair or chancellor Mr Kenneth Clarke say they are committed to full
employment they are deliberately not speaking the language of the average
voter.
Of course both would likely the sort of economic revival that delivered a
job to everyone who wanted one. But all they are promising is the
formulation of the 1944 white paper - a high and stable level of employment.
Whatever that is.
Next the minimum wage. The government insists that any interference in the
rates of pay set by the market is anathema. Depending on what day of the
week it is, ministers proclaim a minimum wage would price hundreds of
thousands or even millions out of work.
They omit to add that the government already imposes a floor on wages - or
more accurately a series of floors - through the benefit system.
In-work benefits have removed the 100 per cent marginal tax rates which used
to apply to those on the bottom end of the income scale. But if an
individual is guaranteed, say, Pounds 120 a week in income support, housing
benefit and council tax rebate he or she is hardly like to jump at a job
paying Pounds 100 a week.
Then there is Mr Blair's commitment to a minimum wage. The pledge apparently
is inviolable. But he will not put a figure on it and certain groups - young
people being the most obvious one - are to be excluded.
Mr Clarke is promising to square one of the circles. He is looking in his
November Budget to an expansion of in-work benefits such as family credit.
His reasons are partly political - the government needs a carrot to put
alongside the stick of tougher rules for unemployed claimants when the new
Job-seekers' Allowance is introduced.
But in the chancellor's mind benefit supplements for those on low wages
allow the government to meet its social obligations without destroying jobs
by re-regulating the labour market. He calls it combining US-style economics
with European-style social policy.
Of course, it is not as simple as that. Just as the benefit level blunts
market forces, so too do income supplements.
Family credit allows employers to maximise profits by keeping wages below
the level the market would otherwise force them to pay. In some cases
in-work benefits simply prolong the life of uneconomic businesses. Taxpayers
employed by more efficient companies provide the subsidy.
But perhaps we should be glad that Mr Clarke's faith in the free market
falls short of his public pronouncements - and, incidentally, that Mr Blair
sees the role of the welfare system as providing a path out of dependency.
The political priority of both parties should be to get many more of the
unskilled unemployed back into work. A few ideological inconsistencies are a
small price to pay.
An extension of in-work benefits from parents to single people and a more
gradual tapering of the rate at which the support is withdrawn as recipients
move up the income scale will provide some but not all the answers.
There are other perversities in the tax and benefit system which make a
mockery of incentives by subjecting the low-paid to effective tax rates of
70 per cent or 80 per cent or by preventing them from taking part-time work.
Remedying that will be expensive in the short-term and will lead to
predictable howls from the Tory right about the numbers of people on
benefit.
More fundamentally, the economy needs a better-educated workforce and a
higher level of productive investment to provide the capacity for a faster
growth rate. Finding the right mix of market forces and government action to
achieve that ambition remains the subject of serious and legitimate
disagreement between the two main parties.
But there should be common cause about the need to do more now to provide an
escape from dependency for the present generation of under-educated,
unskilled workers. Mr Blair and Mr Clarke should tell us for once they
agree.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
