<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Council workers reject 3.9%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local authority employers yesterday increased their pay offer from 3.2 per
cent to 3.9 per cent but it was rejected by unions representing the 1.5m
employees.
Privately, both sides say industrial conflict is highly unlikely. The
employers hinted that a slightly improved final offer will be made on July
21, saying they were 'close to' their limit.
The employers said the offer, which would be paid in two stages and last
until April 1996, would increase the Pounds 14bn pay bill by more than
Pounds 500m.
As the government - which directly funds 85 per cent of local government
spending - is assuming the same pay bill as last year, that means cutting
jobs and services to finance the pay increase.
Mr Charles Nolda, spokesman for the employers, said: 'The government has a
pay bill freeze but it is not policing this pay negotiation in any way. We
are free to do exactly what we want.'
Last year the local authority pay bill did not rise - in spite of a 1.5 per
cent pay increase - thanks to the departure of 50,000 employees. This year,
however, Mr Nolda expects a smaller reduction in staff which means more
services are likely to be cut.
At the next negotiations on July 21 the employers may make further
improvements to the non-pay elements of the deal. Already this year they
have agreed to extend maternity leave arrangements to low-paid part-time
staff, partly as a result of European Court rulings, and agreed five days
paternity leave. The current offer would mean both blue-collar and
white-collar workers receiving an average rise of 2.1 per cent this year and
a further 1.8 per cent from August 1995. This means a 21-month settlement
for white-collar staff and a 19-month offer for manual workers.
Mr Mick Graham of the GMB general union said the deal would mean a pay cut
for workers this year.
</TEXT>
