FT  07 JUL 94 / World Trade News: Yen's rise lifts imports of vehicles to
Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The yen's ability to defy gravity has been a boon to vehicle imports to
Japan, which rose by 40.3 per cent to a record 137,966 units in the first
half of this year, writes William Dawkins in Tokyo.
Sales of imported vehicles climbed by 42.9 per cent last month from a year
earlier, as Japanese consumers took advantage of the falling yen price of
foreign cars.
Overseas plants of Japanese producers have also benefited. Imports of
foreign-made Japanese vehicles nearly doubled last month to just under 9,000
(30 per cent of all imports).
Reuter adds from Washington: The US and Japan broke off trade talks
yesterday and officials said the negotiators had failed to strike any deals
for the Group of Seven summit in Italy this weekend.
The two sides plan to resume talks after the summit, once seen as a deadline
for a deal. But, said a US official, 'we had no expectations (for a G7 deal)
and we have met them.'
