<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / China bans child labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China yesterday published a labour law aimed at protecting workers' rights,
including the outlawing of the employment of children under 16.
The law, which comes into effect next January 1, appeared to be aimed partly
at answering international criticism of China's employment practices, which
have been attacked by human rights groups.
Chinese workers were also promised an eight-hour working day and a minimum
wage, but these conditions are certain to be difficult to enforce given
widely differing work practices across the country.
The new law, which lays down penalties for the mistreatment of workers,
follows criticism of exploitation of workers by foreign employers. China's
press has highlighted recently a number of workers' complaints about harsh
conditions imposed by foreign businessmen.
The labour law, which was published in the People's Daily, the Communist
party newspaper, reinforced regulations passed earlier this year specifying
an eight-hour day and a maximum 44-hour week.
Workers are also guaranteed one day off a week under the new law. Women are
not required to work beyond their seventh month of pregnancy and are
entitled to a 90-day maternity leave. They are also relieved from working in
hardship locations such as mines.
Employers are required to negotiate contracts with employees that lay down
conditions of work, including pay and the nature of work to be done.
Termination arrangements should also be specified.
The law also calls for establishment of disputes committees in work places
to include employers and workers.
In China, trade unionists are invariably members of the Communist party and
do not have a record of militancy in defence of workers' rights.
Nancy Dunne adds from Washington: The Clinton administration was expected
yesterday to greet the reforms with some enthusiasm. With France, it has
linked labour rights to trade, only to be stigmatised for their efforts as
protectionists. The reforms will help garner US support for China's
candidacy in the World Trade Organisation, although there will still be
concerns about enforcement of the new legislation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
