<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / World Cup '94: Brazilian star Leonardo banned for four games
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Brazilian mid-fielder Leonardo was yesterday suspended for four matches
after being sent off for elbowing the USA's Tab Ramos during Monday's World
Cup second-round clash in San Francisco, which Brazil won 1-0.
Leonardo will miss the rest of the tournament and was fined 10,000 Swiss
francs (about Pounds 5,000) for the touch line offence, which left Ramos
with a fractured skull.
The four-match suspension is the heaviest handed out by Fifa at the finals.
Fifa general secretary Sepp Blatter described the incident as the most
aggressive foul of the tournament. 'It was a revenge foul,' he said.
The Brazilian football confederation has three days to appeal, but can
protest against only half the ban, because Fifa's disciplinary committee can
impose a two-match suspension without the right of appeal.
