<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / US opens up energy contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEN WARN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US energy department yesterday unveiled plans to put out to competition
a cluster of contracts worth up to Dollars 27bn at its nuclear and other
sites in a radical change from its previous business practice.
It is also seeking to renegotiate a further Dollars 13.5bn of existing
contracts to secure better value for money.
The department is the federal government's biggest civilian user of
contractors, employing companies or universities to run its national
laboratories, undertake research and - until the cold war ended - design and
produce nuclear weapons. Now it is more concerned with cleaning up the
environment at its nuclear bomb-making plants.
However, under practices that go back to the Manhattan Project, which built
the first US atomic weapon, site contracts were rarely competed for. In the
few cases where competition occurred, the existing contractor was usually
selected.
In the past, management and operating contracts were awarded at nuclear
sites covering every aspect of their running. Now, smaller management
contracts will be awarded at some sites, with as many tasks as possible
monitored for performance, and use made of subcontractors.
Much work was previously awarded on a cost-reimbursement basis, whereby the
contractor presented the government with a bill on completion. In future,
the department will seek to award more work on a fixed price basis. 'In some
cases cost-reimbursement is just like handing a contractor a blank cheque,'
a department official said.
In the first test of the new policy, the department will issue a proposal
for a new-style management contract at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons
complex in Colorado later this month. The plant is currently managed by
EG&amp;G, a Massachusetts-based scientific and technical services company, under
a Dollars 6.4bn five-year contract.
Other areas where competition is planned, as management contracts totalling
Dollars 27bn expire over the next 2-3 years, include the Nevada nuclear test
site and the Idaho national engineering laboratory.
'Most of our contractors are fully supportive of our reform goals,' Mrs
Hazel O'Leary, the energy secretary, said. However, she warned that where
renegotiation of contracts did not produce satisfactory results, the
department would not hesitate to put orders out to competition. In
environmental clean-ups the spectre of competition has produced offers from
contractors to cut costs by 15-20 per cent, officials said.
</TEXT>
