<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Mannesmann chief forgoes new post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mannesmann, one of Germany's largest industrial companies, yesterday
acknowledged growing suggestions of impropriety by Mr Werner Dieter, the
outgoing chief executive, and decided not to elect him chairman of the
company's supervisory board.
The company said Mr Dieter, who will step down as chief executive at the
annual meeting tomorrow, will become an ordinary member of the supervisory
board and not chairman as originally planned.
The decision comes days after the Dusseldorf state prosecutor began
investigating alleged fraud by Mr Dieter, who is said to have forced
Rexroth, a Mannesmann subsidiary, to buy hydraulic accessories at inflated
prices from Hydac, a company largely owned by Mr Dieter's family.
The engineering conglomerate has already ordered an internal enquiry but
this found no evidence against Mr Dieter, 64, who has been chief executive
since 1985.
'The examination of the Mannesmann audit reports to date has not
substantiated any of the charges against Mr Dieter,' the company said. 'For
the sake of a more comprehensive understanding of the subject matter the
supervisory board has decided to commission an external audit by the C&amp;L
Treuarbeit AG.'
The company said Mr Dieter would not seek to become chairman of the
Mannesmann supervisory board, a non-executive board which oversees the
company's management, until the external audit had been completed. Mr
Friedrich Christians, a former chief executive of Deutsche Bank, will stay
on as chairman.
The board also recommended that approval of Mr Dieter's activities as chief
executive - in effect a vote of confidence by shareholders - be postponed
until next year's annual meeting, the earliest date at which he could take
over as chairman.
Mr Dieter recently told the Financial Times the relationship between Rexroth
and Hydac had existed for 31 years and had been openly discussed when he
took over as chief executive in 1985.
He said the companies were 'entirely competitive' and internal company
documents had been leaked in an attempt to wreck his chances of becoming
supervisory board chairman.
Spiegel, the weekly news magazine, first published the allegations against
Mr Dieter a month ago when the company's shares stood at DM446 (Pounds 180).
The shares fell to DM397 last week on news of the state prosecutor's
investigation but picked up DM2 yesterday to DM414.
</TEXT>
