<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Minister criticises Alitalia managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wildcat strikes by Alitalia cabin staff seriously disrupted flights for a
second consecutive day yesterday. Staff are opposing radical restructuring
plans for the loss-making national airline.
Further disruptions are likely through the weekend and a strike by all the
airline's staff is scheduled for July 11. However, an air traffic
controllers' strike planned for today and tomorrow has been postponed for
two weeks.
Mr Publio Fiori, transport minister, unexpectedly announced an inquiry into
the failure of the management to foresee the strike action and avoid
inconvenience to the public.
His criticism of management for ignoring the union behind the strikes risks
undermining the tough proposals in the restructuring plan.
The union yesterday claimed 75 per cent of the domestic and international
flights were cancelled. Alitalia said the figure was 323 flights out of 606.
The union was formed last year by cabin staff who felt the regular unions
did not represent their interests. As it has no more than 300 members out of
the 18,000 Alitalia staff the management excluded it from restructuring
discussion last month. However, the strike has been backed by other unions,
making the impact far greater.
The Alitalia management is discussing with the unions a plan to cut 4,000
jobs and completely rewrite existing work contracts (the pay packets of
cabin crew are calculated on 504 different elements). This is seen as the
first big test of the Berlusconi government's desire to cut restrictive
practices, introduce labour flexibility and reduce the padding in
state-owned groups.
But the labour problems at Alitalia contrasted sharply with a breakthrough
in industrial relations over a new wage and work conditions agreement just
concluded between the employers and the 1.5m members of the engineering
workers' unions. The agreement, reached for the first time without any
strikes, is likely to become the benchmark for all other wage deals -
including key public sector pay talks in the autumn.
The agreement is evidence that union leaders and Confindustria, the
industrialists' confederation, are prepared to adopt a more consensual
approach in the light of last July's labour accord ending indexed wages.
Under the engineering unions' agreement, wages to the end of 1996 will rise
only in line with the official inflation index. There was no attempt to
recover the loss in earning power during the past two years of recessions.
But workers will be entitled to year-end productivity/profitability bonuses.
The average working week will be 39 hours.
</TEXT>
