<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Brussels probes Eko Stahl aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission said it had begun proceedings against Eko Stahl, the
loss-making German steelmaker, into the legality of state aid to the
company. The case increases pressure on the German government to find a way
of saving the plant in former east Germany. A rescue plan collapsed two
months ago. It assumed that Riva, the private Italian steelmaker, would buy
the company, modernise it and cut the workforce from 3,000. Riva's
withdrawal means that loans and guarantees paid to Eko Stahl fall foul of
Commission guidelines. The chances of a buyer being found, however, appear
slim at a time of confusion in the industry over how best to make capacity
cuts. The Commission said yesterday that since early May, the Treuhand
privatisation agency had provided loans of at least DM15.6m (Pounds 6.4m) to
Eko Stahl, and had guaranteed DM149m in bank loans. Brussels also announced
yesterday that it would investigate the granting of loans by the
Hamburgische Landesbank to another steel plant, the Neue Hamburger
Stahlwerke, which may again contravene EU guidelines on state aid. It was
also looking closely at a third steelmaker, Saarstahl, which refused
Commission officials access this week to investigate a DM120m loan to
modernise one of its plants.
</TEXT>
