<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Andreotti may face new charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Palermo magistrates are pressing for more serious charges to be brought
against Mr Giulio Andreotti, former Italian prime minister, over his alleged
links to the Mafia, in an attempt to retain control over the highly
sensitive investigation into the ageing Christian Democrat politician. The
original charge against Mr Andreotti claimed he had links with the Mafia.
Palermo magistrates are now understood to want to change this to an
allegation that, by providing political proection for Cosa Nostra, the
umbrella organisation of the Sicilian Mafia, he was in effect part of the
criminal organisation.
Mr Andreotti has denied the charge and through his lawyers is fighting to
have the case removed from Palermo to Rome, his home base, where he believes
he will obtain a more sympathetic hearing. However, the more serious crime
is alleged to have taken place in Palermo and thus comes under that city's
jurisdiction. 'The important thing is that I have nothing to do with the
Mafia and on this point no public prosectutor or law court could prove the
contrary,' the 73-year-old Mr Andreotti said yesterday. Former Mafia members
now co-operating with the authorities under witness protection allege that
Mr Andreotti provided political cover for Cosa Nostra and that several of
his key political lieutenants in Sicily were members of the Mafia.
</TEXT>
