<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Bonn threatens action on petrol pollutant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Klaus Topfer, Germany's environment minister, warned yesterday that his
country would take its own steps to reduce the level of benzene in petrol
unless the European Union could find a solution. Benzene makes up around 2.5
per cent of petrol and has been identified as a cancer-causing compound. It
also creates low-level ozone, better known as summer smog, which causes
coughing, eye irritation and lung damage. Mr Topfer's remarks, only days
after Germany took over the EU presidency, are further evidence of Bonn's
determination to take unilateral action where it feels other Union members
are dragging their feet.
The Bundesrat, the upper chamber of parliament, will decide tomorrow whether
to approve an import ban on British beef, a measure Mr Horst Seehofer,
health minister, has been campaigning for on the grounds that British
imports may be contaminated with BSE or mad cow disease.
Although the European Commission this week approved a draft directive
designed to reduce the number of air pollutants, repeated German attempts to
start a European initiative to reduce benzene levels have come to nothing,
Ms Marlene Muhe of the environment ministry said.
Ms Muhe said reducing benzene to around 1 per cent of petrol would reduce
exhaust pipe emissions of the chemical by up to 40 per cent, a measure
supported by the Netherlands and Denmark. 'If we want to fight the summer
smog we have to do battle with the substances that create it,' she said.
Unlike lead, benzene is not added to petrol but is created during the
refining process. The environment ministry said German refineries had the
technology to reduce levels to create 'cleaner' petrol.
Ms Muhe said that if Germany opted for unilateral action the European
Commission would be informed of the reduced levels but this would not
require engines to be modified. According to Mr Topfer, the refining changes
would add up to two pfennigs to the cost of petrol.
</TEXT>
