<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Unemployment down in Germany: First fall in west for almost
three years suggests faster recovery in labour market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Seasonally adjusted unemployment in west Germany fell by 3,000 in June. It
was the first drop since autumn 1991, suggesting a more rapid recovery than
expected in the German labour market.
The actual decline in Germany as a whole was 70,900, to 3.59m, with the
largest fall in the east, where the total dropped by 42,800 to under 1.12m.
The rate in the west was 8 per cent, down from 8.1 per cent; and in the
east, 14.8 per cent, compared with 15.4 per cent in June.
The figures were immediately welcomed by the government as proof that
economic recovery is well under way. Chancellor Helmut Kohl told a
conference of industrialists and trade unionists that he expected the
economy to grow more quickly than the 1.5 per cent officially forecast at
the start of the year.
However, the relatively slow pace of economic recovery overall was confirmed
by weaker industrial order figures in west Germany in May, and a downwards
revision of the figures for April.
What the figures do suggest is that domestic economic activity is beginning
to recover, taking over from export demand.
The provisional figures for industrial orders in May showed a fractional 0.1
per cent decline compared with April, which in turn was down 0.5 per cent
against March, after the adjustment. Year-on-year, the May orders were up
8.1 per cent, nevertheless.
The sharpest decrease month-on-month was in export orders, down 1.5 per
cent, whereas domestic orders improved by 0.5 per cent, the federal
statistics office said.
Foreign orders have now been performing less well than domestic orders for
the past two months, and capital goods, in particular, showed a clear
improvement. On the other hand, the year-on-year figures still show a growth
in export orders of 9.4 per cent, compared with just 2.1 per cent for
domestic ones.
In another clear sign that last year's very sharp recession has finished,
the Ifo economic research institute published its forecast of investment
plans, suggesting a marginal 1 per cent fall this year, compared with 20 per
cent last year.
The 1993 investment collapse was actually the sharpest recorded by the
Munich-based institute since it began its investment survey of German
industry in 1955. The researchers blamed it on the combination of an
inflated investment level coinciding with German unification, and the switch
by western enterprises to investing in the east since then.
At the economic conference in Mr Kohl's office, the chancellor warned
against any over-hasty satisfaction with the evidence of recovery, stressing
in particular the problem of structural unemployment. He urged both
employers and unions to concentrate on all possible means of job creation.
The evidence of a real recovery in unemployment will certainly be welcomed
by the governing coalition as useful ammunition for the general election in
October. On the other hand, Mr Theo Waigel, finance minister, is rumoured to
be planning further change in unemployment benefit - restricting eligibility
to just two years before jobless workers have to switch to a lower level of
subsistence-related benefit. He refused to confirm or deny the plan
yesterday, but the opposition Social Democrats are seeking to make maximum
political mileage out of any such cuts which may emerge when the government
publishes its draft 1995 budget next week.
</TEXT>
