<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Courtaulds rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chemicals group Courtaulds benefited from a market reappraisal as one
analyst saw it as a switch opportunity.
Smith New Court has put flesh on the bones of its recent forecast upgrades
with a piece of research pointing out the extent of the global recovery
within the industry. Analyst Mr Charles Lambert said: 'We think the stock
looks temporarily oversold and we would see a 10 per cent upside. It is a
buy on its own merits but BOC looks well up with events, and investors who
do not want to commit further funds to the sector might want to switch.' The
shares ended 12 up at 497p and BOC eased 3 to 702p.
BZW, the investment bank, was largely responsible for the strong
outperformance of the merchant banks against the market, telling its clients
that the sector had been oversold.
Hambros and Kleinwort Benson were the two best individual performers, the
latter closing 8 higher at 442p, after 447p, and the former 5 better at
276p, after 283p. BZW said Hambros was substantially oversold,
underperforming by 13 per cent over one month and 25 per cent over the past
quarter.
The investment bank also pointed out that Hambros traded at a 10 per cent
discount to its 300p a share asset valuation, and offered an attractive
yield of 7.5 per cent and price/ earnings ratio of 9 times. Kleinwort, BZW
said, offered good dividend cover and looked cheap on a price/earnings
basis.
SG Warburg, whose shares have been unsettled by Enterprise Oil's failure in
its attempt to takeover Lasmo - Warburg advised Enterprise - edged up to
699p early in the session but later slipped back to close only a penny ahead
at 694p.
The insurance sectors burst into life, with Commercial Union following
Monday's 11 gain with a rise of 18 to 536p amid strong suggestions that it
is about to withdraw from or reduce the terms of its acquisition of Groupe
Victoire, the French insurance group, from Compagnie de Suez, Victoire's
parent.
Dealers also said that there had been a split order in CU shares yesterday,
which had pushed the stock price sharply higher. Elsewhere in composites,
Sun Alliance held up well, closing only a penny off at 306p, with stories
still circulating that a bid in the sector may not be too far away.
HSBC eased 5 to 689p, with the market beginning to focus on the possibility
that the bank could be lining up a sizeable overseas acquisition. There have
been strong rumours that HSBC has taken a hard look at ANZ Bank. Another
story suggested that HSBC was considering taking a sizeable stake in Nedcor,
the South African bank.
RMC was again the pacemaker in a building sector continuing to respond to
Monday's good news from the Builders Merchants Federation.
The stock was also given a strong push by James Capel, the leading UK agency
broker, which increased its earnings forecast. For the current year Capel is
going for Pounds 235m, up from Pounds 208m, and for 1995 for Pounds 275m,
against Pounds 245m. RMC shares closed 15 higher at 878p.
Builders merchants were featured by Meyer International, up 13 at 417p,
after 419p, with BZW recommending the stock.
CAMAS, the construction materials business demerged from English China Clays
on June 1, rose 5 to 77p, helped by a broker's recommendation.
Brewer Scottish &amp; Newcastle was buffeted by differing opinions following
Monday's figures. Two UK houses were advising clients to sell and one US
investment bank was advising a switch into Bass, which rose 6 to 520p.
Meanwhile, one of the City's leading securities houses took the opportunity
to pick up 400,000 'special ex' shares for its own pension fund, and the
support for a thinly traded stock saw Scottish rebound from its low of 492p
to close 2 off at 499p.
Unilever added 3 at 971p as one of its subsidiaries announced a disposal and
SGST reiterated its long term buy stance.
A stock overhang weakened several motor dealers. Cowie relinquished 10 to
249p, while Lex Service eased 8 to 421p. A squeeze boosted engineering group
GKN, leaving the shares 5 ahead at 571p. A clutch of broker's
recommendations helped components group T&amp;N gain 7 at 231p.
News that GEC has reopened talks on buying Thorn EMI's defence businesses
boosted trading in both stocks. GEC, which reports figures tomorrow, closed
3 ahead at 294p, while Thorn put on 2 to 1001p after trade of 1.2m.
The honour of being the day's best performing stock in the FT-SE 100 went to
British Airways, whose shares jumped 12 to 392p on volume of 6.6m, after it
released better than anticipated traffic figures for the month of June.
Other statistics, Page 41
</TEXT>
