<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Fed concern holds Dow to
narrow gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices ended flat to lower in thin trading yesterday as traders and
investors nervously awaited the outcome of the two-day meeting of the
Federal Reserve's policy-making open market committee, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 5.83 at 3,652.48, well
off a high for the day of 3,667.70. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's
500 ended just 0.17 firmer at 446.37, while the American Stock Exchange
composite lost 1.02 at 423.70 and the Nasdaq composite dipped 3.26 to
703.59. Trading volume on the New York SE was 195.4m shares.
Share prices opened weaker across the board, with the Dow falling 10 points
in early trading as investor concern surfaced that the FOMC, which was due
to start its meeting in the afternoon, might vote to raise interest rates to
protect the dollar. In recent days the US currency has fallen to new
post-1945 lows against the Japanese yen.
The initial equity market decline, however, was not sustained, and prices
quickly moved into positive territory, aided by the stability of the dollar,
which held its own against the yen.
Stock market sentiment was also buoyed by a modest firming in bond prices,
and by a growing feeling among economists that the FOMC would not push up
interest rates just to protect the ailing dollar.
Economists said that the Fed would be more likely to raise rates if there
were fresh evidence of an overheating economy. The fact that this evidence
may come on Friday, when the June employment report is published, ensured
that yesterday's gains in stock prices were short-lived. In fact, demand was
so spotty that secondary indices such as the Russell 2000 small-cap index,
and the Amex and the Nasdaq composites, remained lower for most of the day.
Among individual stocks, Texaco stood out, rising almost Dollars 2 before
ending Dollars  3/4 up at Dollars 60 7/8 in busy trading after the oil group
announced a significant restructuring that will include the sale of more
than half of its US oilfields and a reduction in its worldwide workforce of
about 2,500 within a year.
The strength in Texaco shares provided the rest of the oil sector with a
lift. Mobil rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 82 5/8 , Phillips Petroleum
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 33, Amoco Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 57 3/4 and
Chevron Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 42 7/8 . The exception was Exxon, which
eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 56 7/8 .
Constituents of the Dow were mixed, with some struggling to hold on to early
gains. IBM, which rose Dollars  5/8 at one point, ended Dollars 3/4 down at
Dollars 56 1/4 , but General Electric finished Dollars  5/8 up at Dollars 47
and Philip Morris Dollars  1/2 ahead at Dollars 52 3/8 , all in heavy
trading.
Sony climbed Dollars 3 to Dollars 62 7/8 on news that because of strong
demand the UK manufacturing arm of the Japanese electronics and
entertainment group will be raising production of cathode ray tubes by 50
per cent later this year.
On the Nasdaq market, news of a merger between two computer networking
groups - WellFleet Communications and SynOptics Communications - did not go
down well with investors. WellFleet fell Dollars 5 3/16 to Dollars 20 1/16
and SynOptics lost Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 14 5/8 .
Canada
The Toronto market ended with no clear trend after cautious trade as players
awaited news on the direction of US interest rates.
The Bank of Canada's bank rate fell a greater than expected 30 basis points
to 6.62 per cent in its weekly setting, but the Canadian dollar closed only
modestly lower at 72.10 US cents from Monday's 72.17 US cents.
The TSE 300 composite index showed no change on the day at 4,053.6, while
falls narrowly led rises by 393 to 333 after light volume of 45.1m shares
valued at CDollars 505m.
Eight of the 14 sub-groups were lower, led by golds, off 1.7 per cent as the
bullion price slipped USDollars 1 an ounce to USDollars 385.95 in New York.
The transportation sector showed a gain of 1.0 per cent. Financial services,
mining and energy also finished higher.
</TEXT>
