<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Markets Report: Dollar vigil continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US currency weakened by more than a pfennig yesterday as markets
continued their dollar vigil amid a raft of key policy meetings culminating
in the weekend G7 summit in Naples, writes Philip Gawith.
The growing consensus in the market that no dollar support package is likely
to emerge weakened the US currency, which closed in London at DM1.5826 from
DM1.5965 and against the yen at Y98.825 from Y98.9. In New York it finished
at DM1.5802 and Y98.925.
Elsewhere in Europe the high-yielding currencies - particularly the Italian
lira, Belgian franc and Swedish krona - were under pressure as markets
focused on their large budget deficits.
Sterling closed at DM2.438, a nine-month low, as the weak dollar dragged it
down against the German currency.
The South African financial rand - the foreign investment currency - ended
at R4.845 against the dollar from R4.725 after it emerged that Mr Derek
Keys, the country's influential finance minister, would be resigning later
this year.
As the Federal Open Market Committee, the policy-making arm of the Fed,
started its meeting, markets were increasingly sceptical of the prospect of
any supportive rate moves either in the US or Germany.
The Bundesbank council meets tomorrow, and dollar bulls were hoping that
lower German rates, in tandem with a tightening of US policy, might bolster
the currency.
Mr Jeremy Hawkins, chief economist at Bank of America in London, said the
market was starting to get short of dollars. He said comments from senior
financial officials, downplaying the prospect of concerted intervention, had
encouraged the markets to sell dollars.
Mr Theo Waigel, for example, the German finance minister, said Germany would
not propose the dollar's exchange rate as a subject for discussion at the
Naples summit.
Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Citibank in London, said the market
was, if anything, faced with a yen crisis, not a dollar crisis. He noted
that the dollar was actually stronger against the currencies of its two main
trading partners - Canada and Mexico.
The dollar is also in the middle of its recent trading range against the
D-Mark, between the all-time low of around DM1.40, and the high this year of
DM1.77.
Mr MacKinnon said that inasmuch as central banks were concerned with the
dollar, it was because of 'perceived adverse affects on global financial
markets'. He noted, however, that there are numerous fundamental reasons
why, for example, US bond yields should have risen this year. These include
fears about future inflation, a global capital shortage and the role of
leveraged investors.
The Citibank analyst said, therefore, that he was 'not convinced that
intervention and higher interest rates will strengthen the dollar - and even
if they do, that a stronger dollar will undo the damage that we have seen in
the bond markets'.
Although the dollar is trending weaker, Mr Hawkins said the market was wary
about selling it aggressively short for fear of being caught in a bear trap,
where concerted central bank intervention would move the currency sharply
higher.
The Swedish krona slipped sharply after comments from the finance minister
downgrading the GDP forecast, and raising the budget deficit forecast from
SKr150bn to SKr160bn.
These bad economic numbers come against a complicated political backdrop,
with general elections scheduled in September and the country facing a
potentially difficult referendum on joining the European Union.
The krona closed at SKr4.955 from SKr4.890 against the D-Mark. Mr MacKinnon
of Citibank said it was certainly possible that the krona would again slip
to the low of SKr5.05 that it touched last year.
Two other European countries with large budget deficits, Italy and Belgium,
also saw their currencies weaken. The lira fell back to L993.8 per D-Mark
from L990.6 while the Belgian franc dipped to BFr20.63 from BFr20.61.
Analysts said the move in the Belgian franc was large considering the tight
trading range the currency normally occupies.
The financial rand ended at R4.845 against the dollar, from R4.725 on
Monday, but traders noted that the currency had bounced off a low of
R4.95-8, with some investors sensing value at these lower levels.
The focus of the market now is on who will succeed Mr Keys. Market
speculation favours Mr Conrad Strauss, chairman of the Standard Bank group,
whose appointment would probably calm market nerves.
Activity in the futures markets remained fairly subdued, with trading ranges
narrow at the short end of the market. The December Eurosterling contract
finished unchanged at 93.73, while the December Euromark contract closed at
94.95 from 94.97.
The Bank of England provided late assistance of Pounds 540m to UK money
markets after forecasting a Pounds 900m shortage. Earlier the Bank had
provided Pounds 187m liquidity to the market.
</TEXT>
