FT  06 JUL 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Copper rally runs into
resistance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Copper's price rally continued at the London Metal Exchange yesterday but
ran into resistance short of the 21-month peaks reached late last month.
Twice the three months position spiked above Dollars 2,490 a tonne, but both
times the move was reversed by dealer selling and profit-taking. At the
close the price stood at Dollars 2,486.50 a tonne, up Dollars 17 on the day
and Dollars 110 above the low reached in the sell-off that ended a week ago.
In after hours trading it was trimmed further Dollars 13.
Dealers told Reuter that yesterday afternoon's retreat was all part of a
consolidation process following a week of gains. The rise had been
encouraged by news that Chile's Chuquicamata mine would lose 40,000 tonnes
of output this year because of a furnace closure to comply with pollution
controls.
