<TEXT>
Optus, the Australian telecoms group which was set up as a competitor to the
government-owned Telecom, has confirmed that it plans to float on the
Australian Stock Exchange next year.
The company has appointed County NatWest Corporate Finance to act as its
financial adviser on the flotation, and the two joint lead managers are
County NatWest Securities and Potter Warburg/ABN Amro Hoare Govett.
Optus, licensed as the second telecoms carrier in 1992, is owned by a
consortium of international investors, including BellSouth of the US and
Cable &amp; Wireless of the UK. Australia's Mayne Nickless and several
Australian institutions also have stakes.
