<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / International Company News: Labatt to take stake in Mexican
brewing unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
John Labatt, the Canadian brewing and entertainment group, is expected to
announce today that it is buying a stake in the brewing arm of Femsa,
Mexico's biggest beverage company. The deal is understood to be valued at
about CDollars 1bn (Dollars 714m).
Labatt declined to comment yesterday after trading in its shares was halted
on the Toronto Stock Exchange but the two companies have scheduled press
conferences today.
Labatt, best known in the UK for its Rolling Rock beer and in North America
for its part-ownership of the Toronto Blue Jays baseball team, has
restructured to focus on beer and broadcasting.
It has been seeking another international investment to complement its
brewing interests in the US, UK and Italy.
Last month, Labatt unveiled plans to spin off its sport and live
entertainment businesses. The Toronto branch of the Bronfman family held a
controlling stake in Labatt until early last year, when its shares were sold
to the public.
Femsa's brewing arm, Cerveceria Cuauhtemoc Moctezuma, has just under half of
Mexico's beer market, worth about USDollars 3bn a year.
Philip Morris, the US consumer products group which controls Miller Brewing,
acquired 8 per cent of Femsa's stock in 1992. Femsa held talks with Miller
about an investment in the brewing division, but these have apparently been
unsuccessful.
