<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / International Company News: Digital Equipment may sell
assets to Quantum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Digital Equipment, the struggling US computer company, is discussing the
sale of much of its storage business to Quantum, a fast-growing disk-drive
maker, as part of a radical restructuring Digital is expected to unveil
shortly.
Analysts said the sale, which might raise Dollars 300m to Dollars 400m,
could be just the first of several disposals by Digital as the company sheds
peripheral assets in an attempt to return to profitability.
Digital said yesterday that it was discussing the sale to Quantum of its
magnetic disk, DLT tape drive, solid-state disk drive and thin film heads
businesses. Its storage sub-systems and video and interactive information
services businesses were not part of the discussions.
The company does not have a large presence in disk drives, but it is a force
in the high capacity end of the market, while Quantum, based in Milpitas,
California, is a leading supplier of storage products at the low capacity,
personal computer segment.
Digital, which is based in Maynard, Massachusetts, made an unexpected
Dollars 183m loss in its latest quarter. It is expected shortly to announce
a restructuring plan involving the loss of up to 20,000 jobs, plant closures
and other asset sales.
Mr Robert Palmer, its chief executive, said yesterday that the Quantum
negotiations were part of its overall plan to return the company to
profitability as quickly as possible.
'This effort includes stringent cost controls, focus on those areas where we
can add unique value to our customers and continued staff and facility
reductions.'
He said the company was closely examining which businesses and areas of
technology it needed to supply directly to customers and which areas it made
sense to supply through strategic partners.
Analysts speculated that other assets up for sale could include the
company's software products and its consulting business.
</TEXT>
