<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / International Company News: TWA loses another top executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Trans World Airlines, the US airline struggling to regain financial strength
after emerging from bankruptcy protection last November, yesterday announced
that its vice-chairman had quit.
Mr Robin Wilson, 57, is the second vice-chairman - and the fifth top
executive - to leave TWA this year.
An earlier one, Mr Glenn Zander, resigned in January, shortly after TWA had
announced that speculation about his departure was unfounded.
TWA has also lost a chairman, Mr William Howard, who lasted only a few
months before stepping aside; a senior vice-president for marketing, Mr
Robert Cozzi; and a chief financial officer, Mr Richard Shuyler, who quit
unexpectedly last month to join a small cargo airline without waiting for a
replacement to be named.
TWA last night said it had appointed Mr Mark Coleman, vice-president and
general manager of Avis Wizcom International, as its new senior
vice-president for marketing.
Mr Jeffrey Erickson, who joined TWA as president and chief operating officer
in April, said: 'We're pleased that the TWA team is coming together, and
we're getting the people we need to build TWA's future.'
Last week Standard &amp; Poor's, the US credit rating agency, downgraded its
rating on TWA's debt to triple-C, and revised its rating outlook from
developing to negative. It cited weaker-than-expected revenue generation and
the prospect of a risk to liquidity this winter.
</TEXT>
