<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / International Company News: US computer networking merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wellfleet Communications, the second-largest US manufacturer of computer
network routers, yesterday announced an agreed Dollars 1bn stock swap
takeover of SynOptics Communications, a leading supplier of intelligent
network hubs and switching systems. The deal is the latest example of
consolidation in the US networking industry.
Routers connects networks of computers, while a hub connects desktop
computers to a network.
The two described the deal as a 'merger of equals' between companies sharing
a common vision of open, standards-based network solutions. They claimed it
would position them to move customers to a new generation of
high-performance networks.
However, Wall Street took a mixed view, and Wellfleet's shares closed down
Dollars 5 3/16 at Dollars 20 1/16 . SynOptics, which rose an
unusually-strong 15.6 per cent on Friday, dropped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars
14 5/8 .
Analysts questioned how easy it would be for the smaller, but fast-growing,
New England-based Wellfleet to combine with SynOptics, a California-based
former industry leader which has had several quarters of uninspiring
results.
Several of Wellfleet's rivals, including industry leader Cisco Systems, have
recently acquired switching and hub technology companies. However, the
businesses they bought were significantly smaller than them.
Under the deal, which the two companies hope to complete in October,
SynOptics shareholders will receive 0.725 of a share of Wellfleet stock for
each SynOptics share held. At yesterday's share prices, the deal values
SynOptics at around Dollars 1bn.
Mr Paul Severino, president of Wellfleet, will become chairman of the
combined group. Mr Andrew Ludwick, president and chief executive of
Syn-Optics, will take on the same titles at the new business. There will be
four additional members of the board, two from each company.
Mr Ludwick said the two companies had complementary technologies and
products, while their manufacturing, service and support systems, customer
base and channels were also compatible.
The companies said they intended to develop an end-to-end standards-based
architecture. The key to this would be jointly-developed new products which
combined both routing and switching technologies.
</TEXT>
