<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / The Lex Column: France
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Paris bourse is being torn between fear and greed. It is uncertain which
emotion will prevail. The recent whiff of corruption in the business world,
which is rapidly developing into a stench, has been offending international
investors. Companies accounting for some 16 per cent of the CAC 40's
capitalisation have been tainted by one form of scandal or another. Many of
the allegations may prove unfounded but the damage to sentiment will
persist. The CAC 40 has already fallen 18 per cent this year, substantially
underperforming the German and UK markets. It is not easy to see that trend
quickly reversing itself as political uncertainties mount ahead of next
May's presidential elections.
Nevertheless, investors with steely nerves and long time horizons may sniff
a chance to buy shares on the cheap. Political rows and corruption scandals
are unlikely to knock corporate earnings. Significantly, perhaps, the
savaging of Alcatel's shares on Monday was followed by a sharp rebound the
following day. The French economy also appears to be coming good. The
statistics office yesterday confirmed industrial production had risen 2.1
per cent in April. That may have owed much to a fiscal stimulation package
revving up the car market in particular. But many other industrial groups,
which have squirrelled away provisions during recession, could well produce
some surprisingly good earnings gains.
</TEXT>
