<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Remember the experts who swore that smoking was good for asthma? The experts
who reckoned we were heading straight for a new ice age? And the other
experts who simultaneously warned of the greenhouse effect? Now we are told
that 'Experts believe that inactivity is as dangerous as smoking 20
cigarettes a day' and if today's 'couch potato kids' do not mend their ways
they will cause a national health crisis. This latest danger is addressed in
Open Space (BBC2 8.00). One day someone will have to make a programme
reconciling all the life-threatening phenomena identified by experts with
the fact that life expectancy keeps going up by leaps and bounds. The first
of a new series of Grand Tour (7.20 Radio 4) features Tangiers as seen by
novelist Paul Bowles who has lived in the city since the 1940s. Countryfile
is one of those Barbour-and-wellie programmes which appear to be intended
more for the townie viewer who idealises the countryside than for country
dwellers themselves. Today, presenter John Craven investigates Britain's
largest agricultural show, at Stoneleigh (7.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
